author: @vijaykrishnamenon
text: DS is not just an overlap. DS is the superset of all. ML and DL are all data driven techniques. Right now we have very little AI that does not run on data driven techniques. So DS encompasses all that. Hmm may be AI can have a part outside DS in future like pure exploratory and conditional algorithms (which we don't have as of now) that does not strictly com under the DS set.¬†I rather see them not as subsets at all AI is rightly just writing smart programs, and ML is seen as the Enabling technology, ML has an issue with feature engineering so DL is seen as a enabler interns of automating that. ML and DL have a clear subset relationship, where as contemporary DS is a practiced profession like a set of best practices. I always used a triangular hierarchy diagram so I can be a bit vague when it comes to a subset relation. AI is engineering and programming, ML and DL is Stat and Math (though implementation uses programming), DS is a set of best practices that includes Math, Stat, computer sc. and domain knowledge. We are in the age of data ('driven') solution rather than just another software solution, some thing I do a lot to live.   I ve been teaching AI ML DL and DS for the last 12 yrs at least and now I am a principal data scientist in a respectable company. I have a masters in Software egg and applied sc, another masters in Computational engineering and a PhD in Mathematical Linguistics, with almost 2 decades of experience in the data Space... Gave the credentials so I hope you'll take my advice seriously...   But overall good presentation.

author: @DrDiegoRFaria
text: Minor issues: ML is not only statistical tools, we have classical methods categorised as generative (probabilistic) and discriminative such as SVM, and bio-inspired approach such as ANN. ANN like MLP with one hidden layer is not deep learning, but a ML algorithm. Deep learning are ANNs based algorithms with multiple hidden layers / multiple layers, that's why it is deep, and usually used with huge datasets (CNN and RNN are good examples as explained in the video).  Transfer Learning can be done with a simple ANN (MLP), not only with CNN. Good Video!
